      "content": "The Civil Rights Movement in the US was a pivotal moment in American history, marked by courageous activism and unwavering dedication to equality. The movement began with the Montgomery Bus Boycott (1955-1956), led by Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., which successfully ended segregation on public buses. The March on Washington (1963) and the passage of the Civil Rights Act (1964) and Voting Rights Act (1965) were major milestones, with President Lyndon B. Johnson playing a crucial role in pushing these landmark pieces of legislation. The movement continued with the Selma to Montgomery Marches (1965) and the assassination of Dr. King in 1968, but ultimately paved the way for significant progress in racial equality.",
